[[File:Hunt Light of the World.jpg|right|thumb|''The Light of the World'' (Manchester version)]] '''''The Light of the World''''' (1851–53) is an [[allegorical]] painting by the English Pre-Raphaelite artist [[William Holman Hunt]] (1827–1910) representing the figure of [[Jesus]] preparing to knock on an overgrown and long-unopened door, illustrating [[Book of Revelation|Revelation]] 3:20: "Behold, I stand at the door and knock; if any man hear My voice, and open the door, I will come in to him, and will sup with him, and he with Me". According to Hunt: "I painted the picture with what I thought, unworthy though I was, to be by Divine command, and not simply as a good Subject."<ref name="forbes">{{cite journal|last=Forbes|first=Christopher|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/5671917/images-christ-nineteenth-century|title=Images of Christ In Nineteenth-Century British Paintings In The Forbes Magazine Collection|journal=Magazine Antiques|date=December 2001|volume=160|issue=6|page=794}}</ref> The door in the painting has no handle, and can therefore be opened only from the inside, representing "the obstinately shut mind".{{sfn|Hunt|1905|p=350}} Hunt, 50 years after painting it, felt he had to explain the symbolism.<ref name=VW>{{cite web|url=http://www.victorianweb.org/painting/whh/replete/light.html|work=[[Victorian Web]]|title=The Light of the World|date=December 2001|accessdate=2016-09-03}}</ref>
==Versions== The original is variously said to have been painted at night in a makeshift hut at [[Worcester Park House|Worcester Park Farm]] in Surrey and in the garden of the [[Oxford University Press]]<ref name=EO>{{cite book|editor=[[Christopher Hibbert|Hibbert, Christopher]]|title=[[The Encyclopaedia of Oxford|The Encyclopædia of Oxford]]|location=London|publisher=Macmillan|year=1988|isbn=0-333-39917-X|pages=20, 197, 208-9}}</ref> while it is suggested that Hunt found the dawn light he needed outside [[Bethlehem]] on one of his visits to the Holy Land.<ref name=CHT>{{cite web|title=Chapel History and Treasures|url=http://www.keble.ox.ac.uk/about/chapel/chapel-history-and-treasures|publisher=Keble College|accessdate=2016-09-03}}</ref> In oil on canvas, it was begun around 1849/50,<ref name=CHT/> completed in 1853, exhibited at the [[Royal Academy of Arts|Royal Academy]] in 1854 and is now in a side room off the large chapel at [[Keble College, Oxford]].{{Sfn|Hunt|1905|pp=299–300}}<ref>{{cite book|first=Nick|last=Dalton|title=Frommer's France and the Best of Wales|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NtkCnODXfH8C&pg=PT349|accessdate=2013-01-19|date=2012-08-21|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-33137-8|pages=349–}}</ref> The painting was donated to the college by the widow of [[Thomas Combe]], Printer to the University of Oxford, [[Tractarian]] and a patron of the Pre-Raphaelites, in the year following his death in 1872<ref name=EO/> on the understanding that it would hang in the chapel (constructed 1873&ndash;76) but the building's architect [[William Butterfield]] was opposed to this and made no provision in his design. When the college's library opened in 1878 it was placed there, and was moved to its present position only after the construction in 1892–5 by another architect, [[J. T. Micklethwaite]], of the side chapel to accommodate it.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inside the Chapel|url=http://www.keble.ox.ac.uk/about/tour/inside-chapel|publisher=Keble College|accessdate=2016-09-02}}</ref>
The fact that the college at that time charged a fee to view it<ref name=EO/> persuaded Hunt toward the end of his life to paint a larger, life-size, version, begun about 1900 and completed in 1904, which was purchased by shipowner and social reformer [[Charles Booth (social reformer)|Charles Booth]] and hung in [[St Paul's Cathedral]], [[London]], where it was dedicated in 1908 after a 1905&ndash;07 world tour where the picture drew large crowds.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Light of the World|url=https://www.stpauls.co.uk/history-collections/the-collections/collections-highlights/the-light-of-the-world|publisher=St Paul's Cathedral|accessdate=2016-09-03}}</ref> It was claimed that four-fifths of Australia's population viewed it.<ref name=LF>{{cite web|first=Robert|last=Fulford|authorlink=Robert Fulford (journalist)|title=The Light fantastic: Loved but neglected painting of Jesus became a touchstone of mass culture|url=http://www.robertfulford.com/2007-12-24-hunt.html|work=[[National Post]]|date=2007-12-24|accessdate=2016-09-03}}</ref> Due to Hunt's increasing infirmity and [[glaucoma]], he was assisted in the completion of this version by English painter [[Edward Robert Hughes]] (who also assisted with Hunt's version of ''The Lady of Shalott''). Hunt was buried in St Paul's.<ref>{{cite web|title=William Holman Hunt|work=Find A Grave|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/11800|accessdate=2016-09-03}}</ref>
A third, smaller version of the painting, painted by Hunt in pastels between 1851 and 1856, is on display at [[Manchester City Art Gallery]], England, which purchased it in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Light of the World|url=http://artuk.org/discover/artworks/the-light-of-the-world-205246#|work=Art UK|accessdate=2016-09-03}}</ref>
==Reception== The painting gave rise to much popular devotion in the late Victorian period and inspired several musical works, including [[Arthur Sullivan]]'s 1873 [[oratorio]] ''[[The Light of the World (Sullivan)|The Light of the World]]''.<ref name=VW/> Engraved reproductions were widely hung in nurseries, schools and church buildings.<ref name=LF/>
